## Taofold 1.4.6 is released 🎉

This update is mostly for decreasing volatility of V-trust in the network. We are increasing the epoch length to 300 blocks. We are increasing the threshold of error allowed in the state-checkpoint check to 2% and we are lowering the severity of the punishment of failing the state-checkpoint check from 0 rewards to 0.5 rewards.

* We have added a script called `start_read_node.sh` that will start a read node that connects to the global job pool.

* We have scripts to allow you to query this database called `query_rqlite.py`

Please get accustomed to these scripts as they will be very useful in the future.

git pull

### Miners
No update required but please get accustomed to the new scripts.

# ❤️‍🔥 Announcing v2.0.0 ❤️‍🔥 
Everyone, we at Macrocosmos are so excited to be releasing 2.0.0 to main, which comes with a complete paradigm shift in the subnet. Mainly, this utilizes the complete power of the Global Job Pool for validator job creation and miner data pulling. This is V0 of the pool and it comes with some interesting properties: 
1. As a miner, you are now only queried ONCE for the results of your job. Each job comes with a random update interval between 30 minutes to 2 hours. 
2. Once the reward distribution is determined, this is posted to the pool and all validators utilize this information to incorporate into their scoring vectors. This effectively decreases the noise in the system for miner performance. 

For additional information regarding how this is done, checkout the docs that are provided inside of `folding/documentation/gjp/README.md`. 

There are some important pieces that need to be considered... 

## Miners 💻 
1. You need to make a `.env` file to get proper access to the GJP 
2. Please read the documentation in `folding/documents/mining.md` for information regarding what parameters you need to change (all parameters are inside of `.env.example`) 

## Validators 💡 
Validators do not need to do anything as you are already using the infra of S3 and the GJP. 

## Action Items ◻️ 
We will be increasing the registration cost of the subnet to give miners enough time to adapt their systems to using the GJP and querying. The base miner has been retrofitted with a pipeline that works for querying the system, so please take inspiration from this.

Good question -- the logic is intertwined so I will try and give a simple overview here with respect to the base miner:

1. Miners will NOT receive a job from a single validator to do work, but rather there is a background process that uses the miner's `run` method to check what jobs are inside of the GJP and attempt to add jobs to the workload. This happens in `__enter__` --> `run_in_background_thread` --> `threading.Thread(target=self.run, daemon=True)`

2. The new method `add_active_jobs_from_db` is the method that handles this functionality. If there is capacity to add jobs, we add them through the job's listed priority: 
```python
        query = f"""SELECT job_id, {columns_to_select} FROM jobs 
                   WHERE active = 1 
                   ORDER BY priority DESC LIMIT {jobs_to_fetch}"""
```
So you as a miner will now need to look at the jobs in the pool, decide what you have capacity to work on, and deploy the resources to do so

hey sorry for the delay here man! the setup for optimizing your miner will depend of course on your personal strategies but some general tips: 

1. Try and stop simulations when you believe they are not going to get better. Measuring average change per N steps is a good way to measure this. At some point, simulations plateau even if you keep running them 

2. The more simulations you finish, the better your chances are at getting rewards. It's a decently heavy tailed distribution, so it can be hard to be in the top K (5) submissions 

3. Run 4090s 

4. Think about how you can be *faster*. The best miners on the network here have been here since the start, so they have been figuring out little ways to boost speed. I don't know the entirety of the stack, but there are definitely ways to optimize. Maybe look into different literature online regarding how to improve numerical simulation speeds
